ten despite evidence to the contrary.Hyde approaches HIV/AIDS as a study of the conceptualization and the circulation of a disease across boundaries that requires different kinds of anthropological thinking and methods. She focuses on "everyday AIDS practices" to examine the links between the material and the discursive representations of HIV/AIDS. This book illustrates how representatives of the Chinese government singled out a former kingdom of Thailand, Sipsongpanna, and its indigenous ethnic group, the Tai-Lüe, as carriers of HIV due to a history of prejudice and stigma, and to the geography of the borderlands. Hyde poses questions about the cultural politics of epidemics, state-society relations, Han and non-Han ethnic dynamics, and the rise of an AIDS public health bureaucracy in the post-reform era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAIDS (Disease)xChinaxYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)xGovernment policyxChinaxYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)xGovernment policyzChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectsxChinaxYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aAIDS (Disease)zChinazYunnan Sheng. 0aSidaxAspect socialxChinexYunnan (Sheng)xChinaxYunnan Sheng. 0aSidaxChinexYunnan (Sheng). 0aSidaxPolitique gouvernementalexChinexYunnan (Sheng). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520939486.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d201